<header class="header">
  <h1>How Frost Dates and Growing Degree Days Work Together</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    Frost sets the boundary. Heat determines the outcome.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    <strong>Frost dates tell you how long your season is. Growing Degree Days (GDD) tell you how much growth can happen inside it.</strong>
    If you garden in a short growing season, those are not the same thing — and treating them like they are is one of the most common reasons crops miss maturity before first frost.
  </p>
  <p>
    If you already know your frost dates and want to model heat accumulation inside that window, use the
    <a href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Growing Degree Day Planner</a>.
    To find your typical frost boundaries first, start with the
    <a href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Frost Date Finder</a>.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Frost Dates Define Your Growing Season Boundaries</h2>

  <p>
    Frost dates are climate-based anchors, not promises. GrowByDate uses the 32°F (0°C) frost threshold and frames dates using historical climate normals (1991–2020).
  </p>

  <p>
    Most frost dates are presented at the <strong>50% probability level</strong> — meaning in a typical year there is roughly a 50/50 chance of a 32°F frost occurring on that date or beyond it.
    If you want the plain-language meaning, see
    <a href="/guides/what-does-50-percent-frost-probability-mean/">What Does 50% Frost Probability Mean?</a>.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Last spring frost</strong> helps define when frost-sensitive crops can realistically go outside.</li>
    <li><strong>First fall frost</strong> defines the seasonal cutoff where frost risk begins returning.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    You can find both using the
    <a href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Frost Date Finder</a>,
    or plan specifically around fall risk using the
    <a href="/tools/first-frost-planner/">First Frost Planner</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Why “Frost-Free Days” Isn’t the Same as “Enough Heat”</h2>

  <p>
    Frost dates tell you the length of the window. They do <em>not</em> tell you how warm that window is.
  </p>

  <p>
    Two locations can both have the same frost-free season length — for example, 115–125 days between typical last frost and typical first frost — but accumulate very different total heat.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is the key short-season problem:
    <strong>you can have enough calendar days, but not enough temperature accumulation.</strong>
  </p>

  <p>
    If you want the bigger concept behind this (and why normals aren’t “weather”), see
    <a href="/guides/average-frost-date-vs-actual-weather/">Average Frost Date vs Actual Weather</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>What Growing Degree Days Measure</h2>

  <p>
    Growing Degree Days (GDD) are a way to measure <strong>accumulated heat</strong> over time — the heat plants use to progress through development.
  </p>

  <p>
    A common base temperature for warm-season crops is <strong>50°F (10°C)</strong>. Below that base, growth slows sharply, so those cooler days contribute little or nothing to maturity progress.
  </p>

  <p><strong>Simplified daily GDD formula:</strong></p>

  <pre>
GDD = ((Daily High + Daily Low) ÷ 2) − Base Temperature
  </pre>

  <p>
    Over a season, those daily heat units add up. Many crops and varieties effectively “budget” a certain amount of GDD to reach flowering, fruit set, and maturity.
  </p>

  <p>
    That’s why GDD is the missing half of the planning system: it converts “how long is my season?” into “how much development can I realistically fit into it?”
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>How Frost Dates and GDD Fit Together</h2>

  <p>
    Think of frost dates and GDD as two different constraints:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Frost dates</strong> set the boundaries of your season using a 32°F (0°C) definition.</li>
    <li><strong>GDD</strong> measures how much usable warmth you typically accumulate inside those boundaries.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Frost is the stopwatch. GDD is the fuel.
  </p>

  <p>
    When gardeners rely only on frost dates, they often treat all frost-free days as equally productive.
    In cooler climates, that assumption breaks down because early and late season temperatures can be too mild for fast development —
    especially for warm-season crops like tomatoes, peppers, and winter squash.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>A Simple Example: Same Season Length, Different Outcome</h2>

  <p>
    Imagine two gardeners with the same frost window length in a typical year.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Gardener A</strong> has mild days and cool nights, accumulating about <strong>1,800 GDD (base 50)</strong>.</li>
    <li><strong>Gardener B</strong> has warmer days and nights, accumulating about <strong>2,600 GDD (base 50)</strong>.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The calendar window looks similar — but the maturity outcomes can be completely different.
  </p>

  <p>
    In the lower-GDD climate, long-season crops may still be green when first frost arrives.
    In the higher-GDD climate, those same varieties may finish comfortably.
  </p>

  <p class="fine">
    Note: specific crop requirements vary by variety and base temperature method. GrowByDate’s goal is to help you model the season using typical-year heat accumulation — not promise a guaranteed finish date.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Where the 50% Frost Probability Fits In</h2>

  <p>
    Because frost dates are probability-based, your boundaries are not hard walls. At the 50% level:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Some years your last spring frost happens earlier.</li>
    <li>Some years it happens later.</li>
    <li>Some years first fall frost arrives early.</li>
    <li>Some years it arrives late.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    GDD planning should use the same mindset:
    <strong>you’re modeling what tends to happen in a typical year based on climate normals (1991–2020)</strong>,
    then deciding how much buffer you want based on your risk tolerance.
  </p>

  <p>
    If you want to go deeper on frost as a planning tool (not a promise), see
    <a href="/guides/why-your-last-frost-date-isnt-exact/">Why Your Last Frost Date Isn’t Exact</a>.
  </p>
</section>

