<section class="card">
  <h2>Why This Matters Most in Short Growing Seasons</h2>

  <p>
    In short growing seasons (northern climates, higher elevations, and many inland prairie locations), the limiting factor is often not just “days until frost” —
    it’s “how much heat can I accumulate before frost returns?”
  </p>

  <p>
    That’s why maturity planning works best when you treat frost as the boundary and GDD as the development budget.
  </p>

  <p>
    If you’re close to the cutoff, small advantages can matter — earlier varieties, warm microclimates, or a bit of frost protection.
    But the planning starts with knowing your typical boundaries and typical heat accumulation.
  </p>
</section>

